This study empirically explores the drivers of energy neediness in Pakistan. The investigation's key factors are ‘wellbeing’ and energy poverty as those are the variables ‘health status, a dropout from school, children labour hours, and per capita income.’ This exploration consists of four provinces of Pakistan such as, (Baluchistan, Khyber Pakhtunkhwa (KPK), Punjab, and Sindh) to analyze the observation. The study takes data set from the Pakistan Social and Living Standard Measurement (PSLM) survey and contains from 2003 to 2018. All data sets have taken from Pakistan Bureau of Statistics (PBS) and used the repeated cross-sections of multiple indicator cluster survey (MICS) data. The probability function is used to construct the factor ‘energy poverty,’ which is based on numerous criteria as outlined in the methodology section and notion of energy poverty. If a family member is deemed energy poor, the statistic ‘energy poverty’ assumes the value 1; otherwise, it uses the input 0 (Table 1
                     ). For the individuals who burn through power, particularly families associated with the public framework or off-network utilizing power, the review recommended that per capita power utilization should be over 117 kWh/individual/month or 1400 kWh/individual/year for that individual to be over the energy neediness line (Table 2
                     ). The discoveries (Tables 3–5


                     ) recommended that energy destitution is emphatically connected with old-style fuel consumption of fuelwood, lamp oil for lighting, and in blend with lacking energy use because of ‘exorbitance'.
